Latin America in the fight against the Coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented size and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not face the crisis decisively, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
So far, the political reactions in our region have been very different.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health their top priority.
Others, however, downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, gave their citizens false information, and not only ignored scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These leaders chose a populist and divisive politics in the midst of the tragedy.
Latin America's top priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
Politicians must focus on improving healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily using vacant infrastructure such as hotels or convention centers, and significantly increasing testing capacities.
The Latin American states must also reject export controls on medical supplies and other essential resources, and advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in contrast to US President Donald Trump's reckless decision to freeze approximately $500 million in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacities, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatments and vaccines – in order to ultimately end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: not only has Latin American domestic production been disrupted, but the countries there are also suffering from declining export volumes and prices, income losses from the lack of tourism, and fewer foreign remittances, as well as significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in much of the economy, combined with the collapse in demand, could trigger a contractionary spiral.
To prevent this, bold measures are necessary to protect household incomes.
This means transfer payments to the victims of the crisis, including informal and independent workers who have no access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relief for businesses is also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and payroll costs protect both them and their employees during the crisis. Therefore, they are crucial for a rapid economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of bankruptcies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at that point, the payment system – and with it the entire economy – is at risk.
Many companies, especially the small and medium-sized ones, will experience significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the lack of liquidity will soon become a solvency problem.
Tax deferrals, payment extensions, and subsidized loans will not be enough.
This emergency requires not only unprecedented government guarantees for credit to ensure that banks continue to lend, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and managed state-owned banks can play a leading role in this.
Overall, measures will likely vary by country, but extraordinary fiscal resources will be needed everywhere to accelerate recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activity without worsening health risks.
The problem is that the fiscal space in Latin America is even tighter today than it was after the 2008 global financial crisis.
Therefore, budget adjustments in lower-priority areas must be made to alleviate household burdens.
There is a risk of downgrading creditworthiness, which can be reduced by governments' promises to correct higher budget deficits within a reasonable timeframe.
However, especially for the small and less developed Latin American countries, urgent external support for households and balance sheets is needed.
If both private companies and states take on higher deficits, the countries' current accounts are likely to deteriorate as well.
The recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the largest reversals in modern financial market history – further exacerbate the problem.
The resulting currency devaluations can have a destabilizing impact.
In many economies in the region, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to receive much more external support.
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role here.
It must address the short-term currency and budget needs of countries and continue to support the economies during this crisis, the duration of which is highly uncertain.
To do this, it needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
The Latin American governments should jointly call for a reissue of the IMF's global reserve currency – the Special Drawing Rights, which should reach a volume of one trillion SDRs.
Although SDRs are allocated to member countries based on their IMF quotas, a non-proportional allocation could be achieved by establishing a common pool under the Fund's supervision.
The IMF could also create the necessary capacity to meet the upcoming strong credit demand by immediately doubling the volume of new credit agreements.
And finally, the Fund must improve access to low-barrier tools with rapid disbursement – such as its rapid financing instrument – or introduce new credit facilities for the pandemic, since traditional IMF credit programs are not being approved in time.
Large central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps – either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can pass on liquidity to central banks.
Domestically, central banks must use all available instruments and, if necessary, create new ones to supply financial markets and the economy with enough liquidity.
And finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net disbursements in the region and tap high-liquidity global capital markets to provide further household support.
In exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official lending could be supplemented by debt relief.
The MDBs should also provide countries with guidelines on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – especially for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
Time plays a crucial role in this context.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is unprecedented in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or insufficient responses.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guiding principles in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagoguery.
The crisis should not be used as an excuse to weaken our hard-won civil rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and show what it can offer to its citizens.
